description:
&lt;p&gt;CDDFT are investing an additional £3m into Therapy services across the University Hospital of North Durham (UHND), Darlington Memorial Hospital (DMH) and Bishop Auckland Hospital (BAGH). There has never been a better time to come and join us in developing high quality, evidence based and compassionate therapy services. We are recruiting posts within Physiotherapy, Occupational Therapy, Speech and language Therapy, Podiatry, Dietetics and nutrition, Clinical Psychology and Psychological Practitioners. Look out for all our adverts on NHS jobs.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;As part of this MDT you will have the opportunity to influence the development of:&lt;br /&gt;•integrated pathways across the health and care system&lt;br /&gt;•innovative new roles&lt;br /&gt;•training to upskill our workforce&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;As Therapy services working together we will be able to ensure the care offered is individualised, evidenced based and builds a resilient workforce for the future.&lt;br /&gt;We will also be investing further in our community services to further develop partnership working across the Health and Care System. Contact us for more information on what opportunities are available.&lt;br /&gt;The Adult Occupational Therapy Service is pleased to be able to recruit to a number of band six specialist occupational therapist vacancies to enable the service to expand existing teams and provide a sustainable seven day service across multiple sites.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;There will be permanent posts available at the University Hospital North Durham, Darlington Memorial Hospital and Bishop Auckland Hospital.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;•2 x WTE - University hospital North Durham &lt;br /&gt;•2 x WTE Darlington Memorial Hospital&lt;br /&gt;•4 x WTE Bishop Auckland Hospital&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We are looking for experienced, enthusiastic and highly motivated individuals to join our acute and rehabilitation teams. The post holders will ideally have a range of experience in both acute and rehabilitation settings working in various specialities. They will be able to manage a complex caseload autonomously whilst also providing support for less experienced staff members.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Areas of speciality will include orthopaedics and surgery, respiratory, cardiology, general medical, care of the elderly, frailty and rehabilitation. The post holders will have the opportunity to become specialists in a specific areas but will also be required to work across specialities to support service delivery across all areas of practice within the Adult Occupational Therapy service as required.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;There is an expectation that all staff work flexibly across trust sites and clinic venues if required, although all posts will have a nominal base which is to be agreed upon offer of employment. You must be able to independently travel between sites and undertake home assessment visits independently to fulfil this role.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;When completing your application please specify your preferred choice of nominal base within your supporting information.&lt;/p&gt;
